[2
Date: Mon 26 Mar 2001 13:46:56 +0100
From: Lu Ann McKinney <lmckinney@rvc.ac.uk>

Comment after the article from the Daily Telegraph: [There is a rumour that
the UK epidemic might have had its origins in South Africa. - Mod.MHJ This
is probably based on the 3 Mar 2001 issue of the Veterinary Record, pp
258-259: "Outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease virus serotype O in the UK
caused by a pandemic strain" by Nick J Knowles, Alan R Samuel, Paul R
Davis, R Paul Kitching, and Alex I Donaldson (all of the Institute for
Animal Health (IAH), Pirbright Laboratory, Surrey).
The IAH had isolated and characterized the virus within days of the first
case reports. They compared gene sequences and in an "unrooted
neighbor-joining tree" figure, made clear that the closest homologue of the
UK isolate of the Pan Asia strain is the South African isolate [from the
September 2000 outbreak. It is quite difficult to access back issues of
the Vet Rec online. Reprints may be available from NJ Knowles
(<nick.knowles@bbsrc.ac.uk>).
LuAnn McKinney, DVM, DACVP
The European Centre for Toxicologic Pathology
The Royal Veterinary College
Hawkshead Lane North Mymms
Hatfield, Herts AL9 7TA
[From the Veterinary Record article the difference between the South
African and Essex FMDv isolates is of the order of 0.2%. Otherwise the
nearest (at about 0.6% difference) is the virus responsible for the
Japanese outbreak in 2000. As the South African isolate would have come
from one of the earliest diagnosed outbreaks, a difference of this order
may be explained, if one outbreak was derived directly from the other, [by
time difference and genetic drift. On the other hand, the 2 viruses might
have had a common origin elsewhere. Dr Brueckner clearly insists that all
Pan Asian infected animals in KwaZulu-Natal Province were slaughtered in
late October 2000. The South African experience and the following report
show that there is an active undocumented international trade in meat and
meat products. - Mod.MHJ
